                    <div class="approach-algorithm">
A permutation is a unique arrangement of all elements in an array. To generate all permutations, we want to explore every possible ordering of the elements. Because the number of permutations of an array of length n is n! (factorial of n), the solution naturally involves exploring every choice step-by-step.
<ul>
  <li>Use backtracking to build permutations incrementally.</li>
  <li>Start with an empty path (partial permutation).</li>
  <li>At each step, pick an element that hasn’t been used yet, add it to the current path.</li>
  <li>Recursively continue to build the permutation with remaining elements.</li>
  <li>Once the current path contains all elements, record or print the permutation.</li>
  <li>Backtrack by removing the last added element and try another unused element.</li>
  <li>Repeat until all permutations are generated.</li>
</ul>

